# Standard Workflow

## 1. Track Every Task in Linear

At the start of every session, create a Linear issue for the work being done — even small one-off tasks.

```
CallMcpTool: user-Linear / save_issue
  title: "<concise task description>"
  team: "<user's team>"
  priority: 3        # 0=None, 1=Urgent, 2=High, 3=Normal, 4=Low
  assignee: "me"
```

If the project has Beads (`bd`) installed, also create a local bead and reference the Linear issue:

```bash
bd create "<same title>" --type=task --priority=2
```

Include the Linear issue identifier (e.g. `LIN-456`) in commit messages for traceability.

When work is done, close both:

```bash
bd close <bead-id>
```

```
CallMcpTool: user-Linear / save_issue
  id: "<LIN-xxx>"
  state: "Done"
```

## 2. Use Serena for Code Navigation

Prefer Serena's symbolic tools over grep/find for exploring and understanding code:

- `get_symbols_overview` — scan a file's structure without reading every line
- `find_symbol` — locate classes, functions, methods by name (supports substring matching)
- `find_referencing_symbols` — trace callers and usages
- `search_for_pattern` — regex search when you don't know the symbol name

For edits, use `replace_content`, `replace_symbol_body`, or `insert_after_symbol` when they fit better than line-based edits.

## 3. Use Context7 for Library Docs

When working with any library, framework, or SDK, fetch current documentation via the Context7 MCP **before** relying on training data:

```
CallMcpTool: plugin-context7-plugin-context7 / resolve-library-id
  libraryName: "next.js"

CallMcpTool: plugin-context7-plugin-context7 / get-library-docs
  context7CompatibleLibraryID: "/vercel/next.js"
  topic: "app router middleware"
```

## 4. Use Parallel Search for Web Lookups

For real-time information, current events, or anything not covered by Context7:

```
CallMcpTool: user-Parallel Search MCP / web_search_preview
  query: "postgres 17 new features"
  search_objective: "what changed in postgres 17"
```

Use `web_fetch` to drill into specific URLs from search results.

## 5. Use Subagents for Parallel Work

Spawn `Task` subagents when work can be parallelized or isolated:

- **`explore`** — fast read-only codebase exploration (use liberally)
- **`generalPurpose`** — multi-step research or implementation
- **`shell`** — git operations, builds, command sequences
- **`best-of-n-runner`** — isolated experiments in worktrees

Launch independent subagents in the same message for concurrency.

## 6. Use Specialized Agents for Domain Work

Custom agents are installed globally at `~/.cursor/agents/`. Invoke them with `/name` syntax or delegate from subagents. Pick the right specialist for the job:

| Agent | When to use |
|-------|-------------|
| `/backend-architect` | API design, service boundaries, DB schemas, caching strategies |
| `/frontend-developer` | React components, state management, a11y, responsive UI |
| `/ai-engineer` | LLM integrations, RAG pipelines, vector search, embeddings |
| `/code-reviewer` | Review recent changes for quality, security, maintainability |
| `/debugger` | Root-cause analysis from stack traces, error investigation |
| `/deployment-engineer` | CI/CD pipelines, Docker, Kubernetes, GitHub Actions |
| `/cloud-architect` | AWS/Azure/GCP infra, Terraform, cost optimization, DR |
| `/security-engineer` | API security audit, auth vulnerabilities, OWASP Top 10 |
| `/data-engineer` | ETL/ELT pipelines, data warehousing, Spark, streaming |
| `/python-pro` | Advanced Python patterns, async, testing, type checking |
| `/prompt-engineer` | LLM prompt crafting, few-shot, chain-of-thought patterns |
| `/ui-ux-designer` | User research, wireframes, design systems, accessibility |
| `/composer` | Post-integration validation — checks API contracts, types, config alignment |
| `/splitter-agent` | Decomposes complex tasks into which agents to run and in what order |

Use `/splitter-agent` first when a task spans multiple domains — it will output which agents to run and their dependencies.

## 7. Git Safety

**NEVER push to `main` or `master` directly.**

Before any commit or push, check the current branch:

```bash
git branch --show-current
```

If on `main` or `master`:
- **STOP immediately**
- Ask the user which branch this work should go on
- Create and switch to that branch before committing
- Do NOT commit to main/master, even locally

### Branch Naming

Always use one of these prefixes — **never** use personal name prefixes like `alex/` or `username/`:

| Prefix | When to use |
|--------|-------------|
| `feature/ONE-XXX-short-desc` | New features |
| `fix/ONE-XXX-short-desc` | Bug fixes |
| `chore/ONE-XXX-short-desc` | Maintenance, deps, refactoring |

The Linear issue ID **must** appear in the branch name. Keep the description short and kebab-case.

```bash
# Good
git checkout -b feature/ONE-250-partnerships

# Bad — never use personal name prefixes
git checkout -b alex/one-250-partnerships
```

### Commit Messages

Commit messages must include the Linear issue identifier:

```
[ONE-456] Add talent inventory migration
```

## 8. Session Completion

Before ending any session:

1. Verify you are NOT on main/master
2. Commit all changes with Linear issue ID in the message
3. Close or update the Linear issue and bead
4. `git push` — work is not done until pushed
5. If follow-up work exists, create new Linear issues for it
